Dr. Jill Biden, the Second Lady of the United States, recently visited the Republic of Korea to discuss women's economic opportunities and education. She wanted to learn more about the progress made by women in the country and the challenges they still face. During her visit, she planned to visit schools, meet with teachers and students, and discuss ways to improve quality education for girls and economic opportunities for women. Dr. Biden emphasized the importance of empowering women and girls worldwide and the need for governments, private sectors, civil society, and communities to invest in them. As a working mother and grandmother, she understands the dedication and sacrifice required of women in the workforce. She continues to teach English as a full-time professor and believes that education is crucial for building a better life. Dr. Biden also highlighted the Let Girls Learn initiative launched by President Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama, which aims to support adolescent girls' education globally.